<font color="#FF0000">PTSD SYMPTOMS &amp; VET COUNSELORS</font><br>
<tt>Fri Sep 19 23:31:45 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Art <br>
You're right again about sexually and physically abused individuals experiencing PTSD. How to get their self worth back up can be challenging). <br>
I am looking forward to seeing what you post upstairs regarding PTSD and VN vets. <br>
I found long ago that no one can follow any set pattern in diagnosing individual who experiences are as varied as the time and location as well as the intensities of our various involvements in Nam. I've never looked for a pattern in PTSD and Nam vets, but its easy to see some similarities. <br><br>
What CHET wrote about makes sense; &quot;most of the guys with strong cultural, religious, and strong family background did better.&quot; Perhaps I should add, those that did their duty and didn't consider the political ramifications of their country's involvement faired a lot better as well.  All this seems to be true.<br><br>
A lot of what SW writes about I can associate with, but I had never associated some of those similar symptoms I have experienced with PTSD or in any way with VN. Guess I was just too busy blaming it all on the Clinton administration and commies.<br>
 <br>
I can however understand why so many Vets have become highly effective peer counselors; many of you have posted some though provoking statements above. <br>
I have over 90 books on counseling in my home library, I've read a greater part of them, used them in my duties as a Police Chaplain for the last six years before retirement. I learned a long time ago that if I ever really wanted to help anyone  I needed to put the books away and listen with my eyes and heart.  A listening ear with an understanding heart can work wonders. But a lot still needs clarification. Where is the dividing line, because for vets its not always Nam, but ex-wives, financial problems, children, the boss, that contributes to it all. It's just that Nam became the respectable scapegoat.  <br><br>
Guess what Art has mentioned &quot;There really needs to be more public education and understanding,&quot; is true in more ways then one. But, no one seems to be running to open up any serious debate on all these issues, because of the association with Vietnam. No one wants to touch the issue but we all know its there and inter connected.<br><br>
It seems like our children will have to deal with them in the future in one way or another. I just hope we don't all end up in the same rest home together, a whole new chapter on PTSD would have to be written. <br><br>
Ed, glad to see you back, Pittsburgh State? Is that the place where if you give two or more consecutive lectures on the same topic within a year they make you a professor?  Gee, we might have to begin treating you with a little respect. It's just that its been hard to do that, with you standing there wearing only a P-38 as a cover.<br><br>

<p><code>-- USMC,   (Sparrowhawk) </code><p>


